  "response": "Here's a step-by-step guide to start with competitive coding:\n\n1. Learn a Programming Language\n- Choose a language like C++, Java, or Python\n- Most competitive programmers prefer C++ for its speed\n\n2. Master Basic Algorithms and Data Structures\n- Arrays, Linked Lists\n- Stacks, Queues\n- Trees, Graphs\n- Sorting and searching algorithms\n- Dynamic Programming\n- Recursion\n\n3. Practice Problem-Solving\n- Websites for practice:\n  - Codeforces\n  - LeetCode\n  - HackerRank\n  - CodeChef\n  - SPOJ\n  - AtCoder\n\n4. Study Time and Space Complexity\n- Learn Big O notation\n- Understand algorithm efficiency\n- Optimize your solutions\n\n5. Learn Problem-Solving Techniques\n- Greedy algorithms\n- Divide and conquer\n- Bit manipulation\n- Dynamic programming\n\n6. Online Resources\n- YouTube tutorials\n- Competitive programming books\n- Online courses\n- YouTube channels:\n  - Errichto\n  - William Lin\n  - CP-Algorithms\n\n7. Practice Regularly\n- Solve problems daily\n- Participate in coding contests\n- Track your progress\n\n8. Join Community\n- Competitive programming forums\n- Discord servers\n- Reddit communities\n\n9. Additional Tips\n- Solve past contest problems\n- Analyze solutions\n- Learn from others' approaches\n\nStay consistent and patient!",
